Taiwan Stocks: Catcher, Coretronic, Nan Kang, Yang Ming Marine

-- B y   W e i y i   L i m
-- 
2011-07-15T06:12:47Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-07-15/catcher-coretronic-htc-via-tech-taiwan-stocks-preview.html
Shares of the following companies
had unusual moves in Taiwan trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses and prices are as of the 1:30 p.m. close in Taipei.  The Taiex Index rose 93.56 points, or 1.1 percent, to
8,574.91, halting a six-day slump. The benchmark index dropped 2
percent this week, the first decline in three weeks.  Asustek Computer Inc. (2357)  (2357 TT) gained 4.9 percent to
NT$280, the biggest advance since April 27, after Nomura
Holdings Inc. named the company as one of its top picks for
Asian technology stocks. The brokerage said the company will
likely be able to exceed its shipment target with a new tablet
computer model, according to a report yesterday.  Catcher Technology Co. (2474 TT) gained 2.2 percent to
NT$205. The casing maker had its share-price estimate raised 41
percent to NT$240 at Fubon Securities Co. The brokerage said
high-end metal casings is one of the few industries with strong
orders and pricing power and estimates 15 percent revenue growth
in the third quarter from the previous three months, according
to a report by analyst Jeff Pu.  Coretronic Corp. (5371)  (5371 TT) climbed 5.2 percent to NT$35.45,
gaining for the first time this week. The maker of liquid-
crystal displays and LCD backlights plans to buy back 30 million
common shares, or 4.14 percent of its outstanding stock, the
Hsinchu, Taiwan-based company said in a statement to the stock
exchange yesterday.  Nan Kang Rubber Tire Corp. (2101 TT) jumped by the 7
percent daily limit to NT$52, the highest close since March 26,
1999, on speculation it may get construction rights to its land
in Taipei, said Titan Horng, an analyst at IBT Securities Co.
The land could be used to build apartments or shopping malls,
said Horng. Kuo Mei Hang, a spokeswoman for Nan Kang, didnâ€™t
immediately answer calls to her office.  Yang Ming Marine Transport Corp. (2609)  (2609 TT) surged 6.8
percent to NT$19.60, the biggest advance since Dec. 29, after
oil traded near a three-day low in  New York . Evergreen Marine
Corp. (2603 TT) advanced 1.7 percent to NT$21.25.  China Airlines
Ltd. (2610)  (2610 TT) increased 2.6 percent to NT$17.50.  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
